<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec_damped-reps" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Representations of Damped Harmonic Motion</title>
			
 <subsubsection>
	<title>Activities</title>
	<activity>
		<title>Damped Block I</title>
		<statement>
			<p>
				
			</p>
			<p>
				A block is attached to an ideal spring. At <m>t = 0</m>, the block-spring system, which has non-negligible air resistance, is released from rest at <m>x = 10 \mathrm{~cm}</m>.
			</p>
			<p>
				Which of the following graphs best represents both the position and amplitude functions for the block?
			</p>
			<figure xml:id="fig_damped-ex0">
<title>Choices</title>
    	<caption>Possible graphs for damped harmonic motion.</caption>
    		<image source="damped-ex0.png" width = "100%" ></image>
</figure>
</statement>
		
	</activity>
	<activity>
		<title>Damped Block II</title>
		<introduction>
			<p>
				
			</p>
			<p>
				Suppose the graph below represents the displacement from equilibrium of another block attached to an ideal spring.
			</p>
			<figure xml:id="fig_damped-ex">
<title>Choices</title>
    	<caption>An example graph of damped harmonic motion.</caption>
    		<image source="damped-ex.png" width = "100%" ></image>
</figure>
		</introduction>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					What's the oscillator's displacement at <m>t= 0 \mathrm{~s}</m>?
				</p>
			</statement>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					What is the amplitude at <m>t= 0 \mathrm{~s}</m>?
				</p>
			</statement>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					What is the displacement at <m>t= 2.5 \mathrm{~s}</m>?
				</p>
			</statement>
		</task>
		<task>
			<statement>
				<p>
					What is the amplitude at <m>t= 2.5 \mathrm{~s}</m>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<hint>
				<p>
					You will need to determine <m>\tau</m>.
				</p>
			</hint>
		</task>
	</activity>
	
 </subsubsection>

 <references>
	<biblio xml:id="ref_boxsand-adapt-osc">
	<p>Activities adapted from BoxSand: https://boxsand.physics.oregonstate.edu/welcome.</p>
	</biblio>
</references>
		
</section>

